rom representation theory, the book discusses results about differential equations and their differential galois groups (G) and one-parameter families of exponential sums and their geometric monodromy groups (G). The final part of the book is devoted to comparison theorems relating G and G of suitably "corresponding" situations, which provide a systematic explanation of the remarkable "coincidences" found "by hand" in the hypergeometric case.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aDifferential equations. 0aExponential sums. 7aMATHEMATICS / Differential Equations / General.2bisacsh  aAdjoint representation.  aAlgebraic geometry.  aAlgebraic integer.  aAlgebraically closed field.  aAutomorphism.  aBase change.  aBernard Dwork.  aBig O notation.  aBijection.  aCalculation.  aCharacteristic polynomial.  aCodimension.  aCoefficient.  aCohomology.  aComparison theorem.  aComplex manifold.  aConjugacy class.  aConnected component (graph theory).  aConvolution.  aDeterminant.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDifferential Galois theory.  aDifferential equation.  aDimension (vector space).  aDimension.  aDirect sum.  aDivisor.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aEndomorphism.  aEquation.  aEuler characteristic.  aExistential quantification.  aExponential sum.  aFiber bundle.  aField of fractions.  aFinite field.  aFormal power series.  aFourier transform.  aFundamental group.  aFundamental representation.  aGalois extension.  aGalois group.  aGauss sum.  aGeneric point.  aGroup theory.  aHomomorphism.  aHypergeometric function.  aIdentity component.  aIdentity element.  aInteger.  aIrreducibility (mathematics).  aIrreducible representation.  aIsogeny.  aIsomorphism class.  aL-function.  aLaurent polynomial.  aLie algebra. 